Question 4

We are now ready to do some basic trimming on the text. Do the following on the wordCorpus object using the tm_map() function, and print what’s left of the first paragraph after trimming. (Note: ignore warnings.) * Make all text lowercase * Remove punctuation * Remove numbers * Remove stopwords (e.g., the, a, at, etc.)

customFunct <- function(text) {
  text <- tolower(text)
  text <- removePunctuation(text)
  text <- removeNumbers(text)
  text <- removeWords(text,stopwords("english"))
  return(text)
}
wordCorpus <- tm_map(wordCorpus, content_transformer(customFunct))
print(content(wordCorpus)[1])
## [1] "people flock  kabul airport  taliban seizes capital"

While you call dfm(), make sure to clean the paragraphs by keeping only the stems of the words, removing punctuations, removing symbols, removing numbers, and removing stopwords. If you wish to get rid of anything that does not look correct in the data (such as weird bunch of characters that show up as “words”) you may trim them out at this stage using dfm_remove(). Finally, trim news_dtm such that it contains only words that show up at least 50 times. Print the first 6 rows of news_dtm. (Note: Again, ignore warnings.)

news_dtm <- dfm(newscorpus,

news <- dfm_remove(news_dtm,c(':', '=', 'nt','mp'))
news <- dfm_trim(news_dtm, min_termfreq=50)

Question 15

Plot betas of top 10 words with highest beta for each 8 topic. Comment on 3-4 news headline groups in terms of their topic content.

library(reshape2)
topics <- tidy(topic_model, matrix = "beta")
topWords <- topics %>%
  group_by(topic) %>%
  slice_max(beta, n = 10) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  arrange(topic, -beta) 

topWords %>%
  mutate(term = reorder_within(term, beta, topic)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(beta, term, fill = factor(topic))) + geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Top 10 Words with Highest Beta for Each Topic", x = "Beta Value", y = "Word") +
  facet_wrap(~topic, scales = "free") + 
  scale_y_reordered()

Question 16

Plot gammas of top 5 documents with highest gamma for each 8 topic. Return the contents of the 5 documents with highest gamma only for topics 1 and 2. Does it makes sense that these documents are assigned to topics 1 and 2 accordingly? Comment.

gammaVal <- tidy(topic_model, matrix = "gamma")
documents <- gammaVal %>%
  group_by(topic) %>%
  slice_max(gamma, n = 5) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  arrange(topic, -gamma)
ggplot(documents, aes(x = reorder(document, -gamma), y = gamma, fill = factor(topic)))  + geom_bar(stat = "identity") + labs(title = "Top 5 Documents with Highest Gamma for Each Topic",
       x = "Document", y = "Gamma Value") +
  facet_wrap(~topic, scales = "free_y", ncol = 2)

topdocuments <- documents %>%
  filter(topic %in% c(1, 2))
print(topdocuments)
